00:11:43,021 --> 00:11:45,197
You can't sink.
With all that helium in you,

249
00:11:45,198 --> 00:11:47,084
you're lucky you 
don't float away.

250
00:11:50,701 --> 00:11:52,719
Are you really
admitting defeat?

251
00:11:52,731 --> 00:11:54,020
I never admit defeat.

252
00:11:54,031 --> 00:11:54,889
Good.

253
00:11:54,904 --> 00:11:56,384
However, on an unrelated topic,

254
00:11:56,388 --> 00:11:58,640
I am never getting out
of this bed again.

255
00:11:59,517 --> 00:12:01,487
What if you could
make Kripke

256
00:12:01,489 --> 00:12:03,689
look even sillier
than he made you look?

257
00:12:03,691 --> 00:12:04,863
I don't think
that's possible, dude.

258
00:12:04,863 --> 00:12:05,863
You're not helping.

259
00:12:05,868 --> 00:12:08,324
I didn't come to help,
I came to mock.

260
00:12:09,883 --> 00:12:12,620
Sheldon, what you need to do
is figure out a way

261
00:12:12,630 --> 00:12:15,889
to exact vengeance on Kripke,
like, uh,

262
00:12:16,087 --> 00:12:19,031
like, how the Joker got back
at Batman for putting him

263
00:12:19,034 --> 00:12:21,525
in the Arkham Asylum for
the Criminally Insane.

264
00:12:21,541 --> 00:12:23,629
That's true. He didn't just stay
there and talk about his feelings

265
00:12:23,633 --> 00:12:24,945
with the other
psychotic villains.

266
00:12:24,947 --> 00:12:28,079
He, he broke out and poisoned
Gotham's water supply.

267
00:12:30,439 --> 00:12:31,550
Well...

268
00:12:32,343 --> 00:12:34,406
- I suppose I could poison Kripke.
- No!

269
00:12:34,407 --> 00:12:36,198
- No.
- It's a simple matter.

270
00:12:36,199 --> 00:12:37,431
There are several toxic
chemicals

271
00:12:37,432 --> 00:12:39,552
that'd be untraceable
in an autopsy.

272
00:12:41,450 --> 00:12:43,908
Okay, uh, that's the spirit,

273
00:12:43,931 --> 00:12:46,308
but, um, let's dial it back

274
00:12:46,319 --> 00:12:48,890
to a non-lethal form
of vengeance.

275
00:12:50,105 --> 00:12:51,221
Oh!

276
00:12:52,058 --> 00:12:55,171
How about we put a whoopee 
cushion on his office chair?

277
00:12:55,710 --> 00:12:56,982
He'll sit down,
it'll sound like

278
00:12:56,994 --> 00:12:59,244
he's flatulent,
even though he's not.

279
00:13:01,538 --> 00:13:03,178
Let's keep thinking.

280
00:13:07,740 --> 00:13:09,706
Oh, gee,
you're too late.

281
00:13:09,761 --> 00:13:11,847
Scarlett Johansson and
Wonder Woman were just in here

282
00:13:11,848 --> 00:13:14,502
trolling around for
neurotic, little weasels.

283
00:13:15,281 --> 00:13:18,289
I came to talk to Bernadette.
She's working today, right?

284
00:13:18,322 --> 00:13:20,206
Yes, but I don't think
she wants to see you.

285
00:13:20,220 --> 00:13:21,117
Why not?

286
00:13:21,121 --> 00:13:22,740
Come on, Howard.
You hurt her feelings

287
00:13:22,740 --> 00:13:24,179
by not calling her all week.

288
00:13:24,449 --> 00:13:27,024
Plus, I've kind of been
talkin' some smack about ya.

289
00:13:28,510 --> 00:13:29,553
Hello, Howard.

290
00:13:29,569 --> 00:13:31,479
Wait, Bernadette,
I need to talk to you.

291
00:13:31,567 --> 00:13:32,553
I can't now, I'm working.

292
00:13:32,565 --> 00:13:34,385
This will only take a second.

293
00:13:34,761 --> 00:13:36,180
You asked me
to think about where

294
00:13:36,187 --> 00:13:39,556
our relationship
was going, and I did.

295
00:13:41,067 --> 00:13:41,970
Bernadette?

296
00:13:46,477 --> 00:13:47,868
Will you marry me?

297
00:13:50,190 --> 00:13:52,901
Is this more comedy
that I don't understand?

298
00:13:53,962 --> 00:13:56,255
No. I'm serious.

299
00:13:56,274 --> 00:13:58,830
I'm never going to find
another girl like you

300
00:13:58,837 --> 00:14:02,754
who likes me and is,
you know, real.

301
00:14:04,991 --> 00:14:06,397
So, this isn't a joke?

302
00:14:06,857 --> 00:14:09,184
- No.
- Then you're insane.

303
00:14:10,180 --> 00:14:13,228
I prefer to think
of myself as quirky.

304
00:14:13,819 --> 00:14:16,098
Howard, we've only
been on three dates.

305
00:14:16,368 --> 00:14:18,101
We haven't even had sex yet.

306
00:14:18,316 --> 00:14:20,398
Fair enough.
When's your break?

307
00:14:21,818 --> 00:14:22,628
Wow.

308
00:14:25,875 --> 00:14:27,995
Don't you just hate it
when this happens?

309
00:14:30,251 --> 00:14:31,169
Wow.

310
00:14:34,746 --> 00:14:38,725
All right,
how's this for revenge?

311
00:14:38,736 --> 00:14:41,331
A solution of
hydrogen peroxide,

312
00:14:41,359 --> 00:14:44,807
and one of saturated
potassium iodide.

313
00:14:45,153 --> 00:14:45,865
What's this?

314
00:14:45,877 --> 00:14:47,403
Mountain Dew.

315
00:14:50,373 --> 00:14:51,880
Ahh, refreshing.

316
00:14:51,881 --> 00:14:54,484
Now, we're going to
combine these chemicals

317
00:14:54,485 --> 00:14:55,927
with ordinary dish soap,

318
00:14:55,932 --> 00:15:00,023
creating a little exothermic
release of oxygen.

319
00:15:12,075 --> 00:15:13,300
Foamy vengeance.

320
00:15:13,302 --> 00:15:14,787
Yes, exactly.

321
00:15:14,880 --> 00:15:16,685
This is brilliant, Sheldon.

322
00:15:16,692 --> 00:15:18,583
How are we going to deploy it
in Kripke's office?

323
00:15:18,589 --> 00:15:20,533
Already taken care of.

324
00:15:20,544 --> 00:15:22,003
Observe.

325
00:15:23,069 --> 00:15:26,569
This is a live shot
of Kripke's lab via a mini

326
00:15:26,581 --> 00:15:29,390
webcam I was able to install,
thanks to a dollar bill

327
00:15:29,391 --> 00:15:32,153
discreetly placed in the night
janitor's shirt pocket.

328
00:15:32,303 --> 00:15:33,316
At the same time,

329
00:15:33,316 --> 00:15:35,128
I also secured large quantities

330
00:15:35,134 --> 00:15:38,300
of these chemicals above
the tiles in the drop ceiling.

331
00:15:38,490 --> 00:15:40,098
Oh, Sheldon,

332
00:15:40,109 --> 00:15:42,084
you remind me
of a young Lex Luthor.

333
00:15:44,595 --> 00:15:46,263
You flatter me, sir.

334
00:15:47,087 --> 00:15:49,362
- Let me guess: motion sensors?
- Yes.

335
00:15:49,379 --> 00:15:50,878
The reaction will be triggered

336
00:15:50,888 --> 00:15:53,196
when Kripke reaches
the center of the room.

337
00:15:53,213 --> 00:15:54,949
Mwah, ha, ha.

338
00:15:57,861 --> 00:16:00,673
I gotta say,
I am really impressed.

339
00:16:00,695 --> 00:16:03,722
This is truly the Sheldon Cooper
way to get even.

340
00:16:09,656 --> 00:16:10,866
It may be low-tech,

341
00:16:10,873 --> 00:16:13,995
but I still maintain the whoopee
cushion has comic validity.

342
00:16:15,534 --> 00:16:16,757
Here comes Kripke!

343
00:16:17,555 --> 00:16:18,855
Who is that with him?

344
00:16:19,179 --> 00:16:21,345
I believe that's
the president of the university.

345
00:16:21,344 --> 00:16:23,494
And the board of directors.
Abort! Abort!

346
00:16:23,496 --> 00:16:24,402
There is no "abort".

347
00:16:24,403 --> 00:16:25,888
How could you not put in
an "abort?"

348
00:16:25,891 --> 00:16:27,984
I made a boo-boo, all right?

349
00:16:28,581 --> 00:16:30,306
I think the board
will really appreciate

350
00:16:30,306 --> 00:16:33,170
how well we're using that
NSA grant, President Seibert.

351
00:16:33,172 --> 00:16:35,448
Right here we have
a micro-controlled plasma...

352
00:16:42,900 --> 00:16:45,845
Wow. Looks like the
Ganges on laundry day.

353
00:16:48,722 --> 00:16:50,722
At least they don't
know it was you.

354
00:16:50,972 --> 00:16:52,749
Hello, Kripke.

355
00:16:53,775 --> 00:16:55,884
This classic prank
comes to you

356
00:16:55,906 --> 00:16:59,407
from the malevolent mind
of Sheldon Cooper.

357
00:17:00,161 --> 00:17:01,375
If you'd like to see the look

358
00:17:01,383 --> 00:17:04,156
on your stupid face,
this video is being

359
00:17:04,163 --> 00:17:06,487
instantly uploaded to YouTube.

360
00:17:06,810 --> 00:17:09,655
Oh, and a hat tip
to Leonard Hofstadter

361
00:17:09,662 --> 00:17:12,877
and Raj Koothrappali
for their support

362
00:17:12,882 --> 00:17:15,492
and encouragement
in this enterprise.

363
00:17:18,029 --> 00:17:19,194
Well, I'm going back to India.

364
00:17:19,201 --> 00:17:20,741
What's your plan?

365
00:17:26,823 --> 00:17:28,495
Hey, here's your tip
from table seven.

366
00:17:28,505 --> 00:17:29,870
- Oh, thanks.
- Mm-hmm.

367
00:17:30,027 --> 00:17:31,219
Testing. Check.

